node.text:
This video is from the brilliantly minded Dr Russ Harris, he's a really big name in a therapy called acceptance and commitment therapy, which I can shamelessly say I'm obsessed with. (It works wonders for me and my clients experiencing anxiety, depression, long term health conditions and a bunch more ). So our brains 🧠 have evolved to think negatively in order to keep us safe and alive, that was really really really necessary 1000s of years ago when we were being chased by sabre tooth tigers and stuff, but now... Not so much. Sometimes we think negatively, then get down on ourselves for thinking negatively, making us think even more negatively, You see where I'm going with this ♻️. We need to remember that it's not necessarily our fault that we do this BUT we can decide whether or not we want to continue to do it.

I hope this vid was helpful in explaining how we got here!

Stay tuned for more info tips and tricks ❤️❤️ #motivationmondays

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Dr. Michaela  | Psychologist on July 29, 2021 tagging @myeasytherapy. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'THE TRUTH ABOUT WHY WE PROCRASTINATE @myeasytherapy'.

node.text:
Procrastination = low self esteem…harsh right? This isn’t the case in every single situation sometimes we just don’t want to do ‘the thing’ to avoid feeling bored or tired etc but for many low self esteem has a lot to answer for. Who can relate? 

Ok, so you have a task to do and you're feeling tempted to procrastinate? Now what?⁠
⁠⁠
Try this...⁠⁠
⁠⁠
1. Bring attention to your thoughts: What's the story in your mind. What is your brain telling you. "I'm going to fail at this. I won't do a good job. It will take too long. I'm going to be sooo bored doing it. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Ask yourself - can I have these thoughts and still get the work done.? The answer is usually always YES.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
2. Bring your attention to the sensations in your body. What feelings are triggering your temptation to procrastinate? Anxiety, sadness, boredom. Where do you feel them in your body? What do they remind you of? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Ask yourself. Can I have these feelings and still get the work done.? The answer is usually always YES.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
3. Consider the next action: At the start of a given task, you can consider the next action as just a possibility, as if you were  acting: “What’s the next action I’d take on this if I were going to do it, even though I’m not?” Maybe you would open your email. Or perhaps you would put the date at the top of your document. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
4. Do the'next action'. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
5. BE NICE show self-compassion🤗: Treat yourself with kindness and understanding in the face of your mistakes, forgive yourself in the moments you procrastinate.⁠ There's no point being mean to yourself, it will just keep your threat response activated, maintaining the uncomfortable feelings associated with the task. ⁠⁠

If you're looking at this post scratching your head like how did she know 👀Then get yourself on the waitlist for my upcoming therapeutic group coaching programme Frozen to Fearless. ⁠⁠LINK IN BIO
⁠
P.S ⁠ I’ve got a ridiculously exciting life update to share with you tomorrow so keep your eyes peeled for my IG live at 1pm where I’ll be sharing Errryyyythang

node.text:
Why Emotional Intelligence Was The Key To My Success 
⁠
Ok so in a nutshell emotional intelligence is the ability to identify, understand and manage our own emotions and the emotions of others. Experts agree that this particular type of intelligence plays a vital role in success, and some have suggested that emotional intelligence may be more important than IQ. Wild right?⁠
⁠
At a personal level, emotional intelligence helps you:⁠
⁠
Have those uncomfortable talks without hurting anyone’s feelings⁠
Manage our own emotions when we're stressed and overwhelmed⁠
Improve relationships with the people you care about⁠
⁠
At work, emotional intelligence can help us:⁠
⁠
Resolve conflicts ⁠
Coach and motivate others⁠
Create a culture of collaboration⁠
Build psychological safety within teams⁠
⁠
Unfortunately for me like many people I know I wasn’t taught the basics of emotional intelligence. I wasn’t very self aware, I didn't know how to effectively regulate my emotions, I didn’t know what emotions did what, and most of the time I knew I was feeling ‘something’ but didn't know what to call it...Hello anxiety.⁠
⁠
Our emotions come following whatever thoughts we’re thinking. And when emotions run high, they change the way the brain functions, reducing our ability to think, make decisions, even communicate with other people. Understanding and managing my emotions helped me become more successful in my professional life (I literally wouldn’t have started this page if I didn’t get my emotional intelligence shit together) and relationships. ⁠
⁠
Check out the comments for 5 EI skills and a few ways you can improve them.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Are you a Highly Sensitive Person (HSP)? I definitely am, and very grateful for it.⁠
⁠
Apart from the overthinking, that sucks - For many ambitious and driven people, deep thought is a natural occurrence. For highly sensitive people (HSPs), it can quickly lead to excessive overthinking and anxiety that actually ends up blocking your productivity. ⁠
⁠
Do you know how many people identify with feeling and thinking more deeply, sometimes to an unbearable extent? ⁠
⁠
One in five. ⁠
⁠
Dr Elaine Aron is the psychologist that coined the term in the 90s, and according to her stats 15-20% of the population are highly sensitive - This means they have a more finely calibrated nervous system.⁠
⁠
Dr Aron observed that HSPs are easily overstimulated and emotionally reactive, process information intricately, and are acutely aware of subtleties in ways that non-HSPs are usually not.⁠
⁠
People that are highly sensitive have different challenges when it comes to the workplace:⁠
⁠
Tendency to overthink.⁠
They experience greater levels of work stress⁠ and anxiety⁠
Especially prone to burnout and more impacted by others pain ⁠
They are easily affected by criticism as they respond to other peoples emotions⁠
Higher levels of people pleasing to fend off this criticism⁠
⁠
I’m a HSP myself, and I am very aware that my sensitivity is not a weakness. I see it as a strength that helps me to connect with my clients on a different level. This personality trait is also actually correlated with high-performing behaviors like conscientiousness (hello), empathy (yep), loyalty (I told you), and diligence (that's me) lol. So it’s important to make the best use of these strengths by balancing the downsides.⁠
⁠
If you can relate to these workplace struggles, consider yourself a HSP and want to learn how to use these strengths to your advantage then get yourself on the waitlist for my therapeutic group coaching programme Frozen to Fearless - LINK IN BIO ⁠
⁠
